          <text>
                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Charleston, S. C.</placeName>
                                        <date>May 12. 1853</date>.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)"><addressee>Rev. I. Leeser</addressee>,
                                                  <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">My dear Sir! In sending you the
                                                  <sic>inclosed</sic><lb/> communication for
                                        publication in the Occident, I can not refrain from<lb/>
                                        accompanying it with a few <hi rend="underline"
                                                  >confidential</hi> remarks. In penning<lb/> that
                                        letter, I did indeed not intend to hurt in the least
                                        your<lb/> feelings, or to cast a blame at you, as it has of
                                        late often been<lb/> done, such a thing to you will never
                                        see me do. The letter was<lb/> dictated by feelings of
                                        justice for the absent, and—for yourself;<lb/> for, let me
                                        be candid with you, as it becomes a friend, you<lb/> do
                                        yourself often, very often, injustice, by expressing your
                                        momentary feelings<lb/> in a manner, as you would surely not
                                        have done on second<lb/> reflections.— To show you, that I
                                        harbor no ill feelings for your<lb/> remarks on
                                                  <persName>Dr. Mayer</persName> in
                                                  <placeName>Stuttgard</placeName>, I promise, you
                                        if you<lb/> will accept of it, to send you a translation of
                                        a most masterly<lb/> sketch: “The philosophy and
                                        philosophical writers of the Jews,<lb/> of all times,” by
                                                  <persName>Prof. Munk</persName> in
                                                  <placeName>Paris</placeName>, which I have
                                        received<lb/> a few weeks ago, amongst other new books, and
                                        which afforded me<lb/> to great a pleasure, that I at once
                                                  <del>began</del> commenced a translation of
                                        it.—<lb/> An eulogy on <persName>R. Friedlaender</persName>
                                        has been delivered by <persName>Dr Stein</persName> in<lb/>
                                        <placeName>Frankfurt</placeName>, and is in my
                                        possession—would you publish it?—if<lb/> so, I am ready to
                                        translate it for the Occident.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(7)">With the kindest regards</p>
                              <p rend="indent(8)">I remain yours</p>
                              <p rend="indent(9)">
                                        <persName role="author">Dr M Mayer</persName>
                              </p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">P. S. I need not mention, that the passage in
                                        the<lb/> communication “attacks made of late &amp;c. was not
                                        meant<lb/> for you, but some one else, as you may well
                                        imagine.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(8)">
                                        <persName role="author">M</persName>
                              </p>
